DecoFox !!l3JhOw/FeSb Tue 27 Jul 2021 23:47:00 No.40492205 Report
Quoted By: >>40493129
>>40489289
I would also suggest just trying it, but don't do it out of vanity. Removing meme arrows and mashing the sentences together is not going to make you a good writer as a matter of course. That doesn't mean you shouldn't do it, though.

Greentext is a boon to this thread (and internet in general) because it's kind of a failsafe format. It is possible to write passive-voice and/or overwrought greentext, but it is not the natural state of the thing. Greentext, (if you aren't a newfag and are familiar with how greentext stories are written traditionally on other boards), is good at making even brand new writers accidentally write well. Its first objective is to be clear and succinct, and declarative second person tends to wind up in active voice whether you meant it to be or not. It just so happens that those objectives are huge in any style of prose. It's line-and-stanza organization also tends to make the writer a bit more conscious of rhythm, which goes a long way to varying sentence lengths and structures. These skills are hugely important to prose, but tend to be under-taught in your average high school essay-writing instruction. Greentext endures because the writing style that epitomizes it is considered objectively good by modern western literature standards. If a new writer sets out to write greentext and adhere to the style so as not to come off as a newfag, he will inadvertently be learning to write well in doing it.

All that said, once you're settled in, greentext is just another writing discipline. The important thing to remember in moving to prose is that the point of prose is not to be different from or "more professional" than greentext. In fact, you should be writing your prose to "sound" or "seem" like greentext, even though it isn't. Your tools are a little different because you lose access to free line breaks, but you should still be trying to keep your lines sharp, specific, punchy, and varied.
